There are some small workarounds for this. You can't prevent `amplify push` from overwriting the template, but you can trick it to generate the stack you want, to some extent.

I've found that adding to both `backend-config.json` and `amplify-meta.json` files some data manually (you need to duplicate it in both), and then running `amplify push --force`, makes several changes to the container stack. Specifically:

## Add output parameters from another stack as input parameters

You need to update the `dependsOn` array and add the input parameters you want in the following format:

```json
{
  "category": "",
  "resourceName": <Name of your stack>,
  "attributes": [
    <Name of attribute 1>,
    <Name of attribute 12>,
    ...
  ]
}
```

For example, if you have a container-based API called `"MyContainerApi"` and a custom resource called `"MyCustomResource"` that outputs the attributes `"CustomAttribute1"` and `"CustomAttribute2"`, you `backend-config.json` and `amplify-meta.json` files will initially look similar to this:

```json
{
  "api": {
    "MyContainerApi": {
      "apiType": "REST",
      "build": true,
      "dependsOn": [
        {
          "attributes": [
            "ClusterName",
            "VpcId",
            "VpcCidrBlock",
            "SubnetIds",
            "VpcLinkId",
            "CloudMapNamespaceId"
          ],
          "category": "",
          "resourceName": "NetworkStack"
        }
      ],
      "deploymentMechanism": "FULLY_MANAGED",
      "iamAccessUnavailable": true,
      "imageSource": {
        "type": "CUSTOM"
      },
      "providerPlugin": "awscloudformation",
      "resourceName": "graphql",
      "restrictAccess": false,
      "service": "ElasticContainer",
      "skipHashing": false
    }
  },
  "custom": {
    "MyCustomResource": {
      "dependsOn": [],
      "providerPlugin": "awscloudformation",
      "service": "customCloudformation"
    }
  }
}
```

And the stack name for your custom resource will be something like `"customMyCustomResource"` (you can check the name on your root stack in CF). Then you need to add the following object to the `dependsOn` array of your API:

```json
{
  "category": "",
  "resourceName": "customMyCustomResource", // Name of the stack
  "attributes": [
    // Name of the output attributes you want to input
    "CustomAttribute1",
    "CustomAttribute2"
  ],
}
```

So the file ends up looking like this:

```json
{
  "api": {
    "MyContainerApi": {
      "apiType": "REST",
      "build": true,
      "dependsOn": [
        {
          "attributes": [
            "ClusterName",
            "VpcId",
            "VpcCidrBlock",
            "SubnetIds",
            "VpcLinkId",
            "CloudMapNamespaceId"
          ],
          "category": "",
          "resourceName": "NetworkStack"
        },
        {
          "category": "",
          "resourceName": "customMyCustomResource",
          "attributes": ["CustomAttribute1", "CustomAttribute2"]
        }
      ],
      "deploymentMechanism": "FULLY_MANAGED",
      "iamAccessUnavailable": true,
      "imageSource": {
        "type": "CUSTOM"
      },
      "providerPlugin": "awscloudformation",
      "resourceName": "graphql",
      "restrictAccess": false,
      "service": "ElasticContainer",
      "skipHashing": false
    }
  },
  "custom": {
    "MyCustomResource": {
      "dependsOn": [],
      "providerPlugin": "awscloudformation",
      "service": "customCloudformation"
    }
  }
}
```

Then run `amplify push --force`, and you'll see the parameters in your API stack:

```json
"customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute1": {
  "Type": "String"
},
"customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute2": {
  "Type": "String"
},
```

## Using the parameters as environment variables for your container

Having the parameters is nice, but since you can't make any manual changes to the file, you can't really reference them, so they're kinda useless. I've discovered how to use them as environment variables for a container. You need to add the attribute `"environmentMap"` to your containerized API definition like this:

```json
{
  "environmentMap": {
    "CUSTOM_ATTRIBUTE_1": {
      "Ref": "customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute1"
    },
    "CUSTOM_ATTRIBUTE_2": {
      "Ref": "customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute2"
    }
  }
}
```

So the final definition will be:

```json
{
  "api": {
    "MyContainerApi": {
      "apiType": "REST",
      "build": true,
      "dependsOn": [
        {
          "attributes": [
            "ClusterName",
            "VpcId",
            "VpcCidrBlock",
            "SubnetIds",
            "VpcLinkId",
            "CloudMapNamespaceId"
          ],
          "category": "",
          "resourceName": "NetworkStack"
        },
        {
          "category": "",
          "resourceName": "customMyCustomResource",
          "attributes": ["CustomAttribute1", "CustomAttribute2"]
        }
      ],
      "environmentMap": {
        "CUSTOM_ATTRIBUTE_1": {
          "Ref": "customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute1"
        },
        "CUSTOM_ATTRIBUTE_2": {
          "Ref": "customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute2"
        }
      }
      "deploymentMechanism": "FULLY_MANAGED",
      "iamAccessUnavailable": true,
      "imageSource": {
        "type": "CUSTOM"
      },
      "providerPlugin": "awscloudformation",
      "resourceName": "graphql",
      "restrictAccess": false,
      "service": "ElasticContainer",
      "skipHashing": false
    }
  },
  "custom": {
    "MyCustomResource": {
      "dependsOn": [],
      "providerPlugin": "awscloudformation",
      "service": "customCloudformation"
    }
  }
}
```

You will see how the environment variables are created on your CF template, on the `containersDefinition` section of your Task:

```json
{
  "ContainerDefinitions": [
    {
      "Command": [],
      "EntryPoint": [],
      "Environment": [
        {
          "Name": "CUSTOM_ATTRIBUTE_1",
          "Value": {
            "Ref": "customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute1"
          }
        },
        {
          "Name": "CUSTOM_ATTRIBUTE_2",
          "Value": {
            "Ref": "customMyCustomResourceCustomAttribute2"
          }
        }
      ],
      // ...rest of the container definition
    }
  ]
}
```
